PART 1 — Data Quality Rules ⭐⭐⭐

First — Why Data Quality Matters

Suppose at Amazon:

Orders table contains:

order_id	revenue

101	-5000


Negative revenue.

OR:

customer_id

NULL


OR duplicate orders.

Bad data enters warehouse.

Then:

dashboards wrong

KPIs wrong

executives lose trust

ML models fail


This is why Data Quality Rules exist.


---

What is Data Quality?

Theory

Data Quality ensures data is:

accurate

complete

consistent

valid

reliable


before entering analytical systems.


---

Simple Definition

Data Quality Rules validate and protect warehouse correctness.


---

Common Data Quality Dimensions ⭐

Dimension	Meaning

Accuracy	Correct values
Completeness	No missing critical data
Consistency	Same definitions everywhere
Validity	Follows rules
Uniqueness	No duplicates
Timeliness	Fresh/current data



---

Most Common Data Quality Rules ⭐⭐⭐

1. Null Checks

Critical fields cannot be null.


---

Example

WHERE customer_id IS NULL

Bad data.


---

Real Example

Order without customer:

breaks analytics

breaks joins



---

2. Duplicate Checks ⭐

Duplicate rows create:

double revenue

incorrect metrics



---

Example

GROUP BY order_id
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1

Find duplicates.


---

3. Referential Integrity Checks ⭐

Fact foreign keys must exist in dimensions.


---

Example

Fact row:

customer_key = 101

Must exist in:

dim_customer

Otherwise:

broken joins

orphan facts



---

4. Range Validation

Values must stay within expected range.


---

Example

age < 0
salary < 0
discount > 100%

Clearly invalid.


---

5. Format Validation

Example:

email format

phone format

date format



---

6. Business Rule Validation ⭐

Most important real-world category.


---

Example

delivery_date >= order_date

Business logic validation.


---

7. Freshness Checks

Data must arrive on time.

Example:

daily sales pipeline delayed


Warehouse freshness monitoring required.


---

Data Quality in ETL Pipelines ⭐⭐⭐

Typical flow:

Source Data
    |
Validation Rules
    |
Reject / Fix Bad Records
    |
